	<h2><TMPL_VAR NAME="PAGE_TITLE"> Tips</h2>
	<p><strong>The Business search is targeted so you can find the most you can about a business, from skip tracing, to building a detailed profile or help identify a business relationships. Business records contain information about businesses and government agencies.</strong></p>

	<p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Find a Business record using one or more of the following search techniques:</p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>

	<ol id="font81">
	  <li>Search by Company Name and State. If too many records are returned, try adding a City.<br />
          <br /></li>
	  <li>Search using a Phone Number (including Area Code).<br />
	  <br /></li>
	  <li>Search using a Company's Address, City, and State. This can reveal other companies connected to the business.<br />
	  <br /></li>
	  <li>Search by an individual's Name and State. If too many records are returned, try adding a City.<br />
	  <br /></li>
	  <li>Search by a Company Name and a Radius. If you do not know a Company's city but know the general vicinity, you can use the radius option. Enter a ZIP code or a nearby city and state and provide a radius (in miles) in the Radius field.<br />
	  <br /></li>
	  <li>Search by an individual's SSN.<br />
	  <br /></li>
	  <TMPL_IF COL>
	  <li> Search by SIC Code.  You can either enter the SIC Code directly or select the appropriate industry from the SIC Code Selection Box by clicking on the More Information icon <img src="<TMPL_VAR NAME=IMGPATH>/ico_information.gif" height="13" width="14">.&nbsp; Depending on what other search terms you.ve entered, you may be prompted to enter a City & State, or a Zip Code.<br />
	  </TMPL_IF>
	  <br /></li>
	  </ol>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>


